Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T2]: Malicious Attachments: Droppers

Droppers

A dropper is a piece of code used is to download and install other malware components. Another way attackers use attachments is by embedding a dropper code directly into the attachment. Unlike exploits, this technique has nothing to do with vulnerabilities. Instead, Attackers embed first-stage code in legit files -such as Microsoft documents and PDF files- to download the actual malware payload and execute it.

 

There are many ways to embed code in popular files. For example, attackers can use Macros and DDE to embed code in Office documents.

 

It is worth noting that attackers can directly attach malicious executables such as .exe files, but those rarely make it to the destination inbox. Almost all email servers will catch and block executable attachments, and some even do not allow senders to attach executable files -such as Gmail.

 

Let's look at the following real-world example:

 

Figure - zoom in

 

This is a typical threat SOC analysts experience every day; an email with a Microsoft Excel attachment that can bypass traditional email security controls. It's almost impossible for any business to block Microsoft Office documents.

The first step in similar situations is to check email headers, specifically, the FROM, RETURN-PATH, SPF/DKIM/DMARC verification results.

In the above example, we can tell it's a spam message, but in targeted attacks, attackers spend a lot of time making the malicious email look as legit as possible. They will spoof the FROM header, ensure the absence of SPF/DKIM/DMARC fail signs, and craft the mail body precisely relevant to the victim.

 

Figure - zoom in

 

Looking at the headers, we can see that the SPF result is temperror, the DKIM result is fail, and there is no DMARC header. In typical enterprise networks, email gateways should be configured to stop or at least flag incoming messages that fail SPF or DKIM, or DMARC.

 

Now that we looked at the mail headers, the second step is to inspect the attachment. Suspected attachments should be handled cautiously and analyzed in a safe, isolated environment. SOC analysts can first check the attachment file's hash against widespread threat intel feeds. One of the most prevalent threat feeds sites is VirusTotal

 

Figure - zoom in

 

As we can see, the file has been flagged by different AV engines. Additionally, there are tons of other important information for SOC analysts from a threat intel perspective, such as the DETAILS tab that shows when this file was first submitted for analysis and if it has been seen with different names.

 

Figure - zoom in


As a SOC analyst, you should think twice before uploading or submitting a file for analysis on online services such as VirusTotal. The reason is that attackers regularly check VirusTotal and similar sites to check if their malware has been discovered in the wild. In other words, uploading files to VirusTotal alerts attackers that their attack has been discovered, and they should turn to different ways to compromise the target network.

Many organizations purchase threat feeds services that do not store submitted artifacts or make them public. In addition, organizations can deploy their in-house tools to avoid submitting artifacts to public services.

VirusTotal also offers information about the servers the malware communicates with after successful execution.

 

Figure - zoom in

 

As we can see, the malware contacts two URLs and two IPs. SOC analysts use this information to fortify their networks and discover any badness in their incident response process. The contacted domains could be searched for on the company DNS server and see if any host has queried them, which is a possible sign of compromise.

Not all endpoints/servers in some environments use the company DNS server. In that case, querying the Web Proxy Gateway for hosts that visited the malicious domains can reveal other infections. Also, the network firewall could be searched for any communications with the malicious IPs used by the malware. 

Please note there is an upcoming complete section dedicated to email attacks incident response that discusses the proper steps to take in detail.
 

Another helpful option VirusTotal provides is executing the malware in an isolated/sandboxed environment to determine the behavior of the malware. This information is beneficial for SOC teams who have access to an EDR solution because it allows them to scan their network for possible indicators of compromise (e.g., commands executed, registry keys set or deleted..etc.). 
 

Figure - zoom in

 

Back to the first analysis view, AntiVirus engines flagged this file containing an exploit for Microsoft Office vulnerability CVE-2018-0802. Suppose an end-user opened the attachment using one of the vulnerable and unpatched Microsoft Office versions. In that case, the system will be compromised, and the attacker will gain control of the user machine. 

Note that other security controls can stop the attack even if the user has a vulnerable application. Such as AntiVirus engine, Endpoint Detection and Response (EDR), Host Intrusion Prevention System (HIPS), and hardened configuration/group policy...we will come to this later. That said, it's imperative to adopt a defense-in-depth mentality when looking at threats and ensure that different layers of security controls exist on different levels to stop the threat. When experiencing actual attacks, one does not know which control will stop the threat.

So far, we have discussed popular forms of malicious attachments and seen a real example of a malicious Microsoft Office file. The following section will discuss technical security controls to stop malicious attachments from sneaking into users' inboxes.
